Shoppers's intention online

The dataset contains the following features:

  • Administrative: This is the number of pages of this type (administrative) that the user visited.

  • Administrative_Duration: This is the amount of time spent in this category of pages.

  • Informational: This is the number of pages of this type (informational) that the user visited.

  • Informational_Duration: This is the amount of time spent in this category of pages.

  • ProductRelated: This is the number of pages of this type (product related) that the user visited.

  • ProductRelated_Duration: This is the amount of time spent in this category of pages.

  • BounceRates: The percentage of visitors who enter the website through that page and exit without triggering any additional tasks.

  • ExitRates: The percentage of pageviews on the website that end at that specific page.
  • PageValues: The average value of the page averaged over the value of the target page and/or the completion of an eCommerce transaction. More information about how this is calculated
  • SpecialDay: This value represents the closeness of the browsing date to special days or holidays (eg Mother's Day or Valentine's day) in which the transaction is more likely to be finalized.

  • Month: Contains the month the pageview occurred, in string form.

  • OperatingSystems: An integer value representing the operating system that the user was on when viewing the page.

  • Browser: An integer value representing the browser that the user was using to view the page.

  • Region: An integer value representing which region the user is located in.

  • TrafficType: An integer value representing what type of traffic the user is categorized into. Read more about traffic types here.
  • VisitorType: A string representing whether a visitor is New Visitor, Returning Visitor, or Other.
  • Weekend: A boolean representing whether the session is on a weekend.
  • Revenue: A boolean representing whether or not the user completed the purchase.

Your job

  • Understand the data, visualize it.
  • Use different machine learning's methods to predict shoppers' intention.

Our purpose

  • Prediction results and mean squared error obtained on the test set for the methods you considered.
  • A discussion about the impact of the hyperparameters of the methods on your predictions.
  • A clear comparison between your solutions (a table, and/or plots comparing the results obtained with different methods)

We notice that we have quite a few aberrant valuers. Let's define a function to retrieve all indexes where it is suspected that there are aberrant valuers.

In [ ]:
def find_outliers(v):
  Q1 = np.quantile(v,0.25)
  Q3 = np.quantile(v,0.75)
  EIQ = Q3-Q1
  LI = Q1-(1.5*EIQ)
  LS = Q3 + (1.5*EIQ)
  index = list(v.index[(v<LI) | (v>LS)])
  return index

We see that we do not really have an interest in erasing the 7072 instances otherwise, we lose more than half of the nearly 50% of the data, let's look for another way to be able to remove the outliers.

A another method is to remove outliers by calculating z-score which is equals to (Observation — Mean)/Standard Deviation : $ z_{score} = \frac{(X-μ)}{σ}$.

We find the z score for each of the data point in the dataset and if the z score is greater than 3.5 than we can classify that point as an outlier.

In [ ]:
def remove_outliers(data, l, z):
    for var in l:
        result = data[np.abs(stats.zscore(data[var])) < z]
    return result
  
shop = remove_outliers(shop, numerical_features,3.5)

def scale_column(dataframe,list_columns,scaler):
  i=0
  for col in list_columns:
    dataframe[col]=(scaler.fit_transform(dataframe))[:,i]
    i+=1
  return dataframe

Feature Selection

Consists of choosing the variables with the most importance. One way to do this is to use a forest method. In the trees, the variables are prioritized according to the gini criterion.

According to the gini criterion, at each node of the tree, we choose the variable that maximizes the gini criterion between the remaining variables.

In [ ]:
def model(model_name,method,save=True):
  if(model_name not in ["KNN","neural network"]):
    model1 = method
    model1.fit(x_train,y_train)
  elif(model_name not in ["neural network"]):
    model1=method
    model1.fit(x_train)
  if(model_name not in ["neural network"]):
    y_pred= model1.predict(x_test)
    cm = metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)

  
  
  if(model_name=="neural network"):
    model1=method
    with tf.device('/device:GPU:0'):
      model1.compile(optimizer='sgd',loss='binary_crossentropy',metrics=['accuracy'])
      callback=EarlyStopping(
      monitor='val_loss', min_delta=1e-3, patience=5, verbose=1,
      mode='auto', baseline=None, restore_best_weights=True)
      model1.fit(x_train,y_train,validation_data=(x_test,y_test),callbacks=[callback],batch_size=25,verbose=2,epochs=1000)
      y_pred=model1.predict(x_test)
      classes = np.argmax(y_pred, axis = 1)
      cm=metrics.confusion_matrix(classes,y_test)

  
  print("-----------------------------------------","\n")
  print("Name model: ", model_name)  
  print("-----------------------------------------","\n")

  TP=cm[0,0]
  TN=cm[1,1]
  FN=cm[1,0]
  FP=cm[0,1]
  sensitivity=TP/float(TP+FN)
  specificity=TN/float(TN+FP)


  if(save):
    if(model_name!="neural network" ):
      classifier.append(model_name)
      accuracy.append(accuracy_score(y_pred,y_test))
      missclassification.append(FN+FP)
      auc.append(metrics.roc_auc_score(y_test,y_pred))
    else:
      classifier.append(model_name)
      accuracy.append(accuracy_score(classes,y_test))
      missclassification.append(FN+FP)
      auc.append(metrics.roc_auc_score(y_test,classes))

  if(model_name not in ["neural network"]):
    print("Training Accuracy: ", model1.score(x_train, y_train))
    print("Testing Accuracy: ", model1.score(x_test, y_test))
    print("Accuray_score: ", accuracy_score(y_pred,y_test))
    print("True Negatives :",TN)
    print("True Positives :",TP)
    print("False Negative :",FN," (Type II error)")
    print("False Positives :",FP," (Type I error)")
    print("correctly predicted :",TP+TN)
    print("miss-classified :",FN+FP)
    print("auc :",metrics.roc_auc_score(y_test,y_pred))
  else:
    print(" Training Accuracy",model1.evaluate(x_train,y_train))
    print(" Test Accuracy",model1.evaluate(x_test,y_test))
    print("True Negatives :",TN)
    print("True Positives :",TP)
    print("False Negative :",FN," (Type II error)")
    print("False Positives :",FP," (Type I error)")
    print("correctly predicted :",TP+TN)
    print("miss-classified :",FN+FP)
    print("auc :",metrics.roc_auc_score(y_test,classes))
  plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = (9, 3)
  sns.heatmap(cm, annot = True)
  plt.show()

def wcss_(x):

  wcss = []

  for i in range(1,11):
    km = KMeans(n_clusters=i,init='k-means++', max_iter=500, n_init=3, random_state=0)
    km.fit(x)
    labels = km.labels_
    wcss.append(km.inertia_)

  plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = (15, 7)
  plt.plot(range(1, 11), wcss)
  plt.grid()
  plt.tight_layout()
  plt.title('The Elbow Method', fontsize = 20)
  plt.xlabel('No. of Cluster')
  plt.ylabel('within cluster sum of the square')
  plt.show()

wcss_(new_data)

According to the elbow rule, it is clear that the optimal number of clusters to choose is 2.
